        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In order to examine whether the galaxies (object A, C, and E) are really at the same redshifts (z~1.4) and to study star formation in these systems in terms of molecular gas, we propose CO(3-2) observations toward this system. We will use configuration of C34-7, which gives ~0.3” angular resolution, high enough to separate these galaxies.  The maximum recoverable scale is 6” and is large enough for the target galaxies. 
  The expected minimum CO(3-2) flux density for object A is 0.4 mJy by considering the flux density of CO(5-4) emission line obtained with ALMA.  The velocity width is 150-300 km/s in the previous CO(5-4) emission line. 
  For two other galaxies (object C and object E) in the system, we estimated flux densities of CO(3-2) emission lines from the continuum emission detected in band 6, assuming a dust temperature and emissivity index typical for star-forming galaxies at similar redshift  (Elbaz et al. 2011).  From the continuum emission, we derive FIR luminosity and then obtain CO(3-2) luminosity (L'(CO(3-2)) by using a tight correlation between L(FIR) and  L'(CO(3-2)) (Iono et al. 2009).  Resulting L'(CO(3-2)) are 2.0 x 109 K km s-1 pc2  and 3.4 x 109 K km s-1 pc2  for C and E, respectively. These values correspond to  0.16 Jy km/s  and 0.28 Jy km/s  for C and E, respectively, at the redshift.  If we assume a 200 km/s velocity width, the expected flux densities of CO(3-2)  are 0.8 mJy (object C) and 1.4 mJy (object E), which are larger than 0.4 mJy derived above.  
Hence here we suppose the minimum expected flux density of CO(3-2) line is 0.4 mJy in this system. To detect this line with S/N of 5 in a velocity bin of 200 km/s, we need on-source time of 2.6 hours.  Total observing time from OT is 5.75 hours including overheads.

</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
