    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>During a search for serendipitous source in ‘sub-mJy’ flux density regime with deep 1.3 mm data taken with ALMA , we have found an over dense region of star-forming (SF) galaxies at z=1.4.  Although these galaxies are much fainter than the sub-millimeter galaxies in submm and FIR wavelength region, they show  SF rates of several tens to a few hundreds Msun/yr. Intriguingly, they reside in a 5”(~40 kpc) circle region. Photometric redshifts of two of them are close to the spectroscopic redshift of one of them, suggesting a physical association.  Chance coincidence probability is very low. Thus this is consider to be a pre-merging system and they are expected to form a giant elliptical in futre.  Since a pre-merging system is expected not to show enhanced SF so much, this kind of systems are probably escaped from the previous submm and FIR observations. High sensitivity and high angular resolution observations with ALMA can find such type of object. 
Here we propose CO(3-2) observations toward this system to see whether they are really physically associated or not and to study molecular gas properties (gas mass, extent, gas density, and heating source) in the galaxies. 
</prp:abstract>
